{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510311"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11516"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11516"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.06,0.01,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105998"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105998"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man is referred to the Emergency Department by his general practitioner with a three-day history of erythema, swelling, and pain on his right shin. He noticed these skin changes after sustaining a deep gash to the area following a fall one week ago. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, heart failure, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications are metformin, insulin, perindopril, metoprolol, and aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears flushed and in distress. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 150/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 99% on room air, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. His right shin shows a 9 by 5 cm area of poorly-demarcated erythema with mild swelling that is warm and tender to palpation. There is bilateral pitting oedema up to the distal shin, worse on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous flucloxacillin","Intravenous ciprofloxacin","Oral prednisolone","Surgical debridement","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a tender, warm, erythematous, and swollen right leg following trauma, consistent with cellulitis. For patients with cellulitis or erysipelas \u003Cstrong\u003Ewith systemic features\u003C/strong\u003E who are at low risk of methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E infection, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line therapy. Flucloxacillin is a penicillin antibiotic with good activity against gram-positive organisms, including \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, which are the most common causes of cellulitis. The presence of fever and tachycardia indicates systemic involvement, warranting intravenous therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it has limited activity against gram-positive cocci, particularly \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, and is not recommended for empiric treatment of cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is an immunosuppressant and could worsen the infection by impairing the immune response. It is not indicated in the management of cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical debridement\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for cases where there is evidence of necrotising infection or tissue necrosis, which is not present in this scenario. The absence of skin necrosis or rapidly progressive infection makes this option inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated when there is a localised collection of pus, such as an abscess, in addition to cellulitis. In this case, there is no evidence of a purulent collection, so this intervention is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the most appropriate management is prompt initiation of intravenous flucloxacillin to target the likely pathogens and address the systemic features of infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flucloxacillin is the first-line therapy for cellulitis with systemic features in patients at low risk of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus infection.","Cellulitis presents with erythema, warmth, swelling, and tenderness, often following skin trauma.","Surgical intervention is reserved for cases with abscess formation or necrotising infection."],"references":["Thomas KS, Crook AM, Nunn AJ, Foster KA, Mason JM, Chalmers JR, Nasr IS, Brindle RJ, English J, Meredith SK, Reynolds NJ, de Berker D, Mortimer PS, Williams HC; U.K. Dermatology Clinical Trials Network\u0027s PATCH I Trial Team. Penicillin to prevent recurrent leg cellulitis. N Engl J Med. 2013 May 2;368(18):1695-703. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1206300. PMID: 23635049. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23635049/","Sullivan T, de Barra E. Diagnosis and management of cellulitis. Clin Med (Lond). 2018 Mar;18(2):160-163. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.18-2-160. PMID: 29626022; PMCID: PMC6303460. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6303460/","Cranendonk DR, Opmeer BC, van Agtmael MA, Branger J, Brinkman K, Hoepelman AIM, Lauw FN, Oosterheert JJ, Pijlman AH, Sankatsing SUC, Soetekouw R, Veenstra J, de Vries PJ, Prins JM, Wiersinga WJ. Antibiotic treatment for 6 days versus 12 days in patients with severe cellulitis: a multicentre randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, non-inferiority trial. Clin Microbiol Infect. 2020 May;26(5):606-612. doi: 10.1016/j.cmi.2019.09.019. Epub 2019 Oct 13. PMID: 31618678. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31618678/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11516"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T19:08:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T19:09:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105998"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr